(:kind :chapter :book "Reference Manual" :chapter-number 4 :title "Chapter 4 — Macros" :source-path "git://origin/main/scheme-books/reference/04-macros.md" :size 9728 :sha256 "83536b074c86da76" :content "---\nslug: book-reference-ch-04\nbook: reference\nchapter: 4\ntitle: Macros\npart: appendix\nof: reference-manual\napp: none\ncanonical: true\nowner: docs-team (Lane AJ)\nstatus: draft\nlast-reviewed: 2026-07-10\npalette:\n  background: canvas-cream\n  top-band: magic\n  center: canvas-mint\n  ink: warm-plum\n  pink: sakura-pink (Sakura only)\nprev: 03-tail-recursion\nnext: 05-sicp-flavor\n---\n\n# Chapter 4 — Macros\n\nMacros are where Scheme stops being \"a language you use\" and starts being \"a language you extend.\" The distinguishing feature of the Lisp family, going back sixty years, is that programs and data share the same shape — a list of symbols — so a program can transform another program before it runs.\n\nThis chapter builds five small macros. None of them are exotic; all of them are useful. By the end, you should be able to look at any expression in the reference manual and imagine writing your own control form that expands into it.\n\nSakura Scheme uses `syntax-rules` for pattern-based macros and `define-macro` for procedural ones. This chapter is mostly `syntax-rules` — the pattern form is easier to read and harder to get wrong.\n\n> **Sakura says**\n>\n> The first time I wrote a macro, it felt like cheating — I could invent a keyword. The second time, I noticed I was writing macros for things that didn't need them, and the code got harder to read. The third time, I settled into the actual rule: macros are for a shape of code you write more than once. Not for cleverness; for repetition.\n\n## `when` and `unless`\n\nStandard R5RS has `if` but the two-armed shape wants an \"else.\" `when` and `unless` are one-armed conditionals — run the body if the test is true (or false).\n\n```scheme\n(define-syntax when\n  (syntax-rules ()\n    ((when test body ...)\n     (if test (begin body ...) #f))))\n\n(define-syntax unless\n  (syntax-rules ()\n    ((unless test body ...)\n     (if test #f (begin body ...)))))\n\n(when (> 5 3)\n  (display 'five-is-greater) (newline))\n\n(unless (> 3 5)\n  (display 'three-is-not-greater) (newline))\n```\n\nOutput:\n\n```\nfive-is-greater\nthree-is-not-greater\n```\n\nTwo macros, two lines of expansion each. `when` is `if` with a `begin` and a `#f` for the false branch; `unless` is the same shape with the branches swapped. That's the whole macro.\n\n## `swap!` — a mutation macro\n\n`swap!` exchanges the values of two variables. It has to be a macro (not a function) because a function receives the *values* of its arguments and can't reach back to mutate the names.\n\n```scheme\n(define-syntax swap!\n  (syntax-rules ()\n    ((swap! a b)\n     (let ((tmp a))\n       (set! a b)\n       (set! b tmp)))))\n\n(define x 1)\n(define y 2)\n\n(display (list 'before x y)) (newline)\n(swap! x y)\n(display (list 'after  x y)) (newline)\n```\n\nOutput:\n\n```\n(before 1 2)\n(after 2 1)\n```\n\nThe macro expands `(swap! x y)` into a `let` that binds `tmp` to `x`'s current value, then reassigns `x` and `y`. If `swap!` were a function, `a` and `b` would be values (say, `1` and `2`) and you couldn't `set!` a value — the macro sees the *names* `x` and `y` and rewrites the code around them.\n\n## `for-range` — a bounded loop\n\nA `for` loop over an integer range, expressed as a macro that expands into a tail-recursive `let`.\n\n```scheme\n(define-syntax for-range\n  (syntax-rules ()\n    ((for-range var from to body ...)\n     (let loop ((var from))\n       (cond ((>= var to) 'done)\n             (else body ...\n                   (loop (+ var 1))))))))\n\n(for-range i 0 5\n  (display 'iter) (display \": \") (display i) (newline))\n```\n\nOutput:\n\n```\niter: 0\niter: 1\niter: 2\niter: 3\niter: 4\n```\n\nThe macro takes a variable name (`i`), a start (`0`), an end (`5`), and a body. It expands into a tail-recursive `let` that increments the variable and runs the body. The user writes `for-range` and never sees the `loop` name at all.\n\n## `and*` — short-circuit conjunction\n\n`and` is a Scheme special form; this exercise reproduces it. Not because you'd use `and*` over the built-in, but because building it is the shortest tour of \"macro that expands recursively into itself.\"\n\n```scheme\n(define-syntax and*\n  (syntax-rules ()\n    ((and*)                #t)\n    ((and* a)              a)\n    ((and* a rest ...)     (if a (and* rest ...) #f))))\n\n(display (and*))                (newline)\n(display (and* #t))             (newline)\n(display (and* #t #t #t))       (newline)\n(display (and* #t #f #t))       (newline)\n(display (and* 1 2 3))          (newline)  ;; last truthy value wins in real 'and', not this one\n```\n\nOutput:\n\n```\n#t\n#t\n#t\n#f\n3\n```\n\nThree pattern rules, matched in order. The empty case gives `#t`; the one-argument case gives that argument (so `(and* 5)` returns `5`); the many-argument case picks off one and recurses on the rest. The macro expander walks the recursion at compile time and leaves a nested `if` in the emitted code.\n\n## Peeking at the expansion\n\nYou can ask the reader to show you what a macro expands into. In Sakura Scheme, `,expand` at the REPL prints the expansion of a form without running it.\n\n```scheme\n;; simulating what ,expand would print:\n(define-syntax when\n  (syntax-rules ()\n    ((when test body ...)\n     (if test (begin body ...) #f))))\n\n(define expanded-when\n  '(if (> 5 3) (begin (display 'yes) (newline)) #f))\n\n(display expanded-when) (newline)\n```\n\nOutput:\n\n```\n(if (> 5 3) (begin (display yes) (newline)) #f)\n```\n\nThat's what `(when (> 5 3) (display 'yes) (newline))` becomes before the runtime touches it. The macro rewrote the code, and only the rewritten form actually runs.\n\n## `let/named` demonstration\n\nA slightly bigger macro: a `let/named` form that pretends to be a named `let` (which Scheme already has, but showing the macro shape is the point).\n\n```scheme\n(define-syntax let/named\n  (syntax-rules ()\n    ((let/named name ((var val) ...) body ...)\n     (letrec ((name (lambda (var ...) body ...)))\n       (name val ...)))))\n\n(define (fact-with-macro n)\n  (let/named loop ((k n) (acc 1))\n    (cond ((= k 0) acc)\n          (else (loop (- k 1) (* acc k))))))\n\n(display (fact-with-macro 5))  (newline)\n(display (fact-with-macro 10)) (newline)\n```\n\nOutput:\n\n```\n120\n3628800\n```\n\nThe macro expands `let/named` into a `letrec` that defines the loop as a recursive lambda, then calls it with the initial values. Standard Scheme has `let` do this out of the box; the macro shows why it's not black magic — it's just a shape.\n\n## When a macro is the wrong tool\n\nMacros can implement things functions can't (like `swap!`), but most of the time functions are the right tool. This exercise builds a macro that *should* be a function, so you can feel the difference.\n\n```scheme\n;; a macro version of \"add three numbers\" — bad taste\n(define-syntax add3-macro\n  (syntax-rules ()\n    ((add3-macro a b c)\n     (+ a b c))))\n\n;; the function version — correct taste\n(define (add3 a b c) (+ a b c))\n\n(display (add3-macro 1 2 3)) (newline)\n(display (add3 1 2 3))       (newline)\n```\n\nOutput:\n\n```\n6\n6\n```\n\nSame answer, but the function is preferable: it can be passed as a value, it can be tail-called, it doesn't force its arguments to be literal expressions at the callsite. Macros are for shapes of code that functions can't express — mutation, control flow, syntax extension — not for saving a couple of parens.\n\n> **Warning**\n>\n> The most common macro mistake is writing a macro for something a function would do. If the code you're macro-izing doesn't need to touch names, control flow, or the shape of its arguments, write a function.\n\n## Hygiene — why `syntax-rules` is safe\n\n`syntax-rules` macros are hygienic: identifiers introduced by the macro do not collide with identifiers in the surrounding code. That's why `swap!` above can name its temp `tmp` without worrying about the caller having a variable named `tmp`.\n\n```scheme\n(define-syntax swap!\n  (syntax-rules ()\n    ((swap! a b)\n     (let ((tmp a))\n       (set! a b)\n       (set! b tmp)))))\n\n(define tmp 'outer-tmp)\n(define x 1)\n(define y 2)\n\n(swap! x y)\n(display (list x y tmp)) (newline)\n```\n\nOutput:\n\n```\n(2 1 outer-tmp)\n```\n\nThe outer `tmp` is not clobbered. `syntax-rules` renamed the macro's inner `tmp` behind the scenes.\n\n## Under the hood — expansion time versus run time\n\n> **Under the hood**\n>\n> Macros run *before* the program does — at read/expand time. When Sakura Scheme reads your source, it walks the tree, finds every macro use, and rewrites each into the shape the macro's pattern says. What the evaluator sees is post-expansion code, with no macro forms left in it. This is why macros can invent control flow (they emit `if`, `let`, `set!` in the expansion) but can't do anything at run time — by run time, the macros are gone.\n\n## What you know now\n\n- Macros transform code before it runs.\n- `syntax-rules` is the pattern-based, hygienic form; use it by default.\n- `when`, `unless`, `swap!`, `for-range` are all short pattern-matching macros.\n- Macros are the right tool when you need to touch names, control flow, or the shape of arguments.\n- Functions are the right tool for everything else.\n- `syntax-rules` handles hygiene for you — inner identifiers don't collide with outer ones.\n\n## Try before you turn the page\n\nAuthor a macro `dotimes` that runs its body `n` times without exposing the counter.\n\n```scheme\n(define-syntax dotimes\n  (syntax-rules ()\n    ((dotimes n body ...)\n     (let loop ((k 0))\n       (cond ((>= k n) 'done)\n             (else body ...\n                   (loop (+ k 1))))))))\n\n(dotimes 3\n  (display '*) (newline))\n```\n\nExpected output:\n\n```\n*\n*\n*\n```\n\nIf your `dotimes` doesn't leak a `k` variable into the surrounding scope — which the hygienic `syntax-rules` guarantees — you're done, and Chapter 5 is waiting.\n\n---\n\n*Chapter 5 — A tiny metacircular evaluator.*\n")
